    <h1 id="great-blue-heron-eggs-chicks-and-growing-up">Great Blue Heron Eggs, Chicks, and Growing Up</h1>
<h2 id="the-numbers">The numbers</h2>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Stage</th>
<th>Detail</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Clutch size</td>
<td>2–6 eggs (typically 3–5; average ~4)<sup id="fnref:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup><sup id="fnref3:2"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:2">2</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Egg appearance</td>
<td>Pale blue, fading slightly with age; a little larger than a chicken egg<sup id="fnref2:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup><sup id="fnref5:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Egg dimensions</td>
<td>2.4–3.0 in × 1.8–2.0 in (6.1–7.6 × 4.5–5 cm)<sup id="fnref3:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Laying interval</td>
<td>About every 2 days (asynchronous)<sup id="fnref6:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup><sup id="fnref4:4"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:4">4</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Incubation</td>
<td>25–30 days (commonly 27–29), shared by both parents<sup id="fnref4:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup><sup id="fnref:5"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:5">5</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Hatching</td>
<td>Eyes open, covered in pale gray down, able to vocalize<sup id="fnref5:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>First flight</td>
<td>~60 days (range 49–81 days in nest)<sup id="fnref6:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup><sup id="fnref2:5"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:5">5</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Independence</td>
<td>~10–12 weeks; parents and young then part ways<sup id="fnref7:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup><sup id="fnref5:4"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:4">4</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>First breeding</td>
<td>Not until at least 2 years old<sup id="fnref6:4"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:4">4</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Broods per year</td>
<td>1 in the north; sometimes 2 in the south; up to 2 replacement clutches after failure<sup id="fnref7:4"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:4">4</a></sup><sup id="fnref3:5"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:5">5</a></sup></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h2 id="hatching-into-a-hierarchy">Hatching into a hierarchy</h2>
<p>Because eggs are laid at two-day intervals and incubation starts early, chicks hatch <strong>asynchronously</strong> — the oldest may be nearly a week ahead of the youngest. That head start matters: older siblings intimidate younger ones to claim more food, and in lean years the smallest chicks starve, a grim but common outcome known as siblicide.<sup id="fnref:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup> In a typical brood, only about <strong>two young survive</strong>; mortality comes from starvation, falls from the nest, predators such as raccoons, and human disturbance.<sup id="fnref:4"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:4">4</a></sup></p>
<h2 id="feeding-the-machine">Feeding the machine</h2>
<p>Both parents feed the chicks by <strong>regurgitation</strong> — at first directly into the chicks' open bills, later simply depositing partially digested fish into the nest bottom for the young to pick up.<sup id="fnref2:4"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:4">4</a></sup><sup id="fnref:6"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:6">6</a></sup> Chicks stimulate feeding by pulling the parent's bill downward.<sup id="fnref2:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup> Growth is explosive: from about <strong>50 g at hatching to roughly 2 kg at fledging — a 40-fold gain in eight weeks</strong> — and a family of four needs around 2,000 calories a day, keeping both parents foraging nearly nonstop.<sup id="fnref:2"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:2">2</a></sup> For the first 3–4 weeks one parent broods constantly (typically the male by day, the female by night); after that, both parents hunt.<sup id="fnref2:2"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:2">2</a></sup><sup id="fnref2:6"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:6">6</a></sup></p>
<h2 id="milestones-to-first-flight">Milestones to first flight</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Weeks 1–4</strong>: downy gray chicks, brooded day and night; fed by regurgitation.<sup id="fnref3:4"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:4">4</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>~Week 6</strong>: chicks reach near adult size.<sup id="fnref3:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>~Week 7</strong>: vigorous wing-flapping; hopping branch to branch ("branching").<sup id="fnref3:6"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:6">6</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>~Week 8</strong>: first flights.<sup id="fnref4:6"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:6">6</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Weeks 10–12</strong>: young disperse; families dissolve — herons do not stay together after the season.<sup id="fnref4:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup><sup id="fnref5:6"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:6">6</a></sup></li>
</ul>
<h2 id="watched-by-millions">Watched by millions</h2>
<p>The Cornell Lab of Ornithology's nest cam at Sapsucker Woods, New York — streaming since 2012 from a nest 40 feet up a dead white oak that herons have used since 2009 — gave the public an intimate record of this process. In 2012 and 2013 the pair laid five eggs each year; viewers watched the parents incubate through snowstorms, defend against a nighttime Great Horned Owl attack, and raise all eight hatched chicks to fledging.<sup id="fnref:7"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:7">7</a></sup> The cam documented real-time egg-laying 48 hours apart and the chicks' loud clacking food-begging — details now embedded in the nesting timeline on this page.<sup id="fnref:8"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:8">8</a></sup></p>
